Introduction to rjags: A Bayesian linear regression model

Jan-30-2025

The root directory for this project has 3 folders: “data”, “src” and “run”. The source Rmd file (this file) is in the “run” directory. The “data” directory contains a dataset from the National Cancer Institute’s Surveillance, Epidemiology and End Results (SEER) database. This report presents a Bayesian linear regression analysis of the Stockton real estate dataset. The objective is to model the relationship between the outcome variable Y (home values) and covariates X1 through X6 using Bayesian methods implemented via JAGS. The dataset is analyzed to identify significant predictors of home values and assess the model’s predictive performance. The “src” directory includes a file “modelJags.txt” that encodes a Bayesian linear regression model in the JAGS language and an R program called “dataPrep.r” to prepare the data for the JAGS model.

  1. Remove all objects from the R workspace—good programming practice and can help debug your code better.
rm(list = ls())
  1. Load “rjags” and “coda” packages
library(rjags)
library(coda)
  1. Prepare the data by running the “dataPrep.r” file in the “src” directory.
source("../src/dataPrep.r")
  1. We initialize the unknown parameters in the JAGS model.
inits = list(
                list(beta = rep(0, times=p), tausq=1.0, yFit = rep(0, times=N))
)
  1. Set the following parameters for Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC):
nSamp = 10000 ## Number of posterior samples for inference
nChains = 1 ## Number of chains
nAdapt = 200 ## The initial number of runs to tune parameters
nBurn = 1000 ## Number of initial runs ("burn" period) for MCMC to converge
  1. Define a set of model parameters for JAGS to recognize
modelParameters = c("beta", "tausq", "sigmasq", "yFit")
  1. Compile the Bayesian model
m <- jags.model("../src/modelJags.txt", data=jagsData, inits=inits, n.chains=nChains, n.adapt=nAdapt)
## Compiling model graph
##    Resolving undeclared variables
##    Allocating nodes

##    Total graph size: 15073
## 
## Initializing model
  1. Update the model for the burn-in period
update(m, n.iter=nBurn)

  1. Sample from the posterior distribution for inference
mOut <- coda.samples(model=m, variable.names=modelParameters, n.iter=nSamp)

  1. Scatter plot of observed vs. fitted median values
# Extracting the median fitted values
head(ciyFit) 
##              50%     2.5%    97.5%
## yFit[1] 12.54096 12.23675 12.84619
## yFit[2] 11.60533 11.30117 11.91092
## yFit[3] 12.07481 11.76300 12.37711
## yFit[4] 11.31149 11.01537 11.62230
## yFit[5] 11.25219 10.94937 11.56653
## yFit[6] 11.84547 11.54250 12.14214
yFitMedians <- ciyFit[, 1]  # First column contains the medians

# Scatter Plot: Observed vs. Fitted Median Values
plot(Y, yFitMedians, 
     main = "Observed vs. Fitted Median Values", 
     xlab = "Observed Y", 
     ylab = "Fitted Median Y", 
     pch = 19, 
     col = "blue")

# Add a 45-degree reference line
abline(0, 1, col = "red", lwd = 2, lty = 2)

# Calculate and Display Correlation
correlation_result <- cor(Y, yFitMedians)

# Adding correlation value to the plot
legend("topleft", legend = paste("Correlation =", round(correlation_result, 3)), 
       bty = "n", text.col = "darkred", cex = 0.9)

# Display correlation value in console as well
print(paste("Correlation between Observed Y and Fitted Median Y:", round(correlation_result, 3)))
## [1] "Correlation between Observed Y and Fitted Median Y: 0.896"
